					<p>
						The issue of mental illness in youth has received increased attention from the White House and Congress, as well as the media in recent years. As a respected leader in this discussion, Children's National  held an inaugural summit last year to advance practical and policy solutions for the improvement of mental health access and treatment for children in the United States. The Summit brought together more than 150 key leaders in healthcare, government, and academia to define workable solutions to the challenges facing children and families suffering from mental illness. Speakers such as Virginia Health and Human Resources Secretary William A. Hazel Jr., MD, and Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy worked in partnership with roundtable discussions led by the Division of Psychology and Behavioral Health and included professionals recently impacted by the problem at both the state and local level. During the Summit, attendees volunteered to actively work toward solutions targeting the youth mental health crisis. Discussion topics included workforce issues, trauma-informed mental health care, and de-stigmatizing the diagnosis of mental health issues.
